### Describe the bug
I'm trying to create a custom component containing an input text element, and only allowing numeric values  within a specified range. If the provided value is out of the range, it should change back to the minimum or the maximum value, whichever is closer. However, when trying to use this component, it will only re-render if the value actually changed from one value to a different value. Otherwise, changing to the same value doesn't affect the input element which retains the entered, incorrect value.

I'm trying to figure out what's the best way to achieve this, and whether there is a problem with the way rendering works or if I don't understand it properly.

`NumberInput.razor`
```csharp
<input value="@Value"
       @onchange="InputChanged"
       class="form-control @(IsValid ? string.Empty : "is-invalid")"
       id="@Id"
       name="@Name">

@code {
    [Parameter]
    public bool IsValid { get; set; } = true;

    [Parameter]
    public string Id { get; set; }

    [Parameter]
    public string Name { get; set; }

    [Parameter]
    public int Min { get; set; }

    [Parameter]
    public int Max { get; set; }

    [Parameter]
    public int? Value { get; set; }

    [Parameter]
    public EventCallback<int?> ValueChanged { get; set; }

    private async Task InputChanged(ChangeEventArgs e)
    {
        // If the received value is not numeric then just reset the input with empty
        if (!int.TryParse(e.Value?.ToString() ?? string.Empty, out var value))
        {
            await ValueChanged.InvokeAsync(null);
            return;
        }

        Value = value switch
        {
            _ when value > Max => Max,
            _ when value < Min => Min,
            _ => value
        };

        await ValueChanged.InvokeAsync(Value);
        // StateHasChanged(); // Even when this is uncommented it doesn't make the component to re-render
    }
}
```

`Parent component using the above`
```csharp
<NumberInput @bind-Value="Model.CompletionPercent" IsValid="@Model.IsCompletionPercentValid" Min="0" Max="100" />
```

### To Reproduce
- Use the above component
- Enter value 99
- The value 99 will show as expected in the input element
- Enter value 101
- The value will change to 100 as expected, given that it's the maximum allowed value
- Enter value 101 again

Expected outcome
- The value will change to 100 again

Actual outcome
- The value remains displaying as 101

Please note that the above outcome will also occur even if `StateHasChanged` is invoked after each `InputChanged` trigger. It looks like because the parent component receives the same value (100), the `NumberInput` doesn't re-render. I don't understand though why invoking `StateHasChanged` doesn't change the behaviour.

### Describe the bug
Using `ConfigureKestrel(options =>{ options.Listen(IPAddress.Loopback,` there is a 2 second delay before responding to a request from a Grpc client. This delay is not present when using `ConfigureKestrel(options =>{ options.ListenLocalhost(`, which should be equivalent. This also applies to `options.Listen(IPAddress.Any,` compared to `options.ListenAnyIP(`. I would expect both to be equivalent.

### To Reproduce
Start with the standard Grpc Greeter sample: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/aspnet/core/tutorials/grpc/grpc-start?view=aspnetcore-6.0&tabs=visual-studio (or https://github.com/dotnet/AspNetCore.Docs/tree/main/aspnetcore/tutorials/grpc/grpc-start/sample6)

Modify it by adding to the server Program.cs, before `builder.Build()`:

```c#
builder.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(options =>
{
    options.Listen(IPAddress.Loopback, 7091, configure =>
    {
        configure.UseHttps();
    });
});
```

Run the client and note a 2 second delay before the SayHelloAsync call returns.

Modify the code to instead be:

```c#
builder.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(options =>
{
    options.ListenLocalhost(7091, configure =>
    {
        configure.UseHttps();
    });
});
```

Note that there is no delay when running the client. The same test can be done with `options.Listen(IPAddress.Any,` compared to `options.ListenAnyIP(`

Tested under net6.0 and net5.0

